[1] USA (Minnesota ex Washington)
Date: Fri 13 Jan 2017
Source: CDC Epi-X [edited]
https://epix2.cdc.gov/v2/Reports/StandardReport/Display.aspx?id=61612&print=False&PSR=False


A case of mumps has been reported in an individual who participated in "The Clash XV", a wrestling tournament in Rochester, MN on 30-31 Dec 2016. Teams from 16 states participated in the event, and wrestlers from 4 states had direct contact with the case and will be notified separately. [A total of 600 individuals were potentially exposed].

The Minnesota Department of Health received notification from the Washington State Department of Health that a Washington resident who participated in The Clash tournament on 30-31 Dec 2016 was reported as a mumps case in their ongoing outbreak. Symptom onset was early January 2017, and the case was infectious during the wrestling tournament. Participants in the event included individuals from Washington, Minnesota, North Dakota, California, Georgia, Arizona, Illinois, Oregon, Florida, Missouri, Wisconsin, South Dakota, New England, Ohio, Alabama, and Utah. Four states, including Minnesota, Illinois, California, and Oregon had team members who were directly exposed to the case and will be notified individually.

Mumps can occur in persons with 2 doses of measles, mumps, and rubella vaccine (MMR) with intense and repeated exposure. Precautions for mumps infection include making sure people are up to date with 2 doses of MMR vaccine, practicing good hand hygiene, and isolating symptomatic persons to avoid other exposures.

Wrestlers or other participants who develop parotitis or other mumps-compatible illness (e.g., orchitis, oophoritis) regardless of vaccine status, should follow-up with their health care provider, inform the provider that they may have been exposed to a mumps case, and take precautions against exposing others.

