[The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention expects the nationwide spike in mumps cases to continue into next month [February 2017].

According to the CDC, mumps cases hit a 10-year high in late December 2016, with 5311 cases in the US.

Two of the largest outbreaks happened on university campuses in Iowa and Illinois; 220 cases were also reported at the University of Missouri by mid-December [2016].

The case count is lower than in 2006, when more than 6500 people were sickened. It's also down dramatically since the U.S. began its vaccination program in 1967. Before the push to get vaccinated, roughly 186 000 mumps cases were reported each year.

The measles, mumps and rubella vaccine prevents most, but not all, cases of mumps, health officials say. Two doses of the vaccine are 88 percent effective at protecting against mumps; one dose is 78 percent effective, according to the CDC (Excerpted from: http://woodtv.com/2017/01/13/cdc-mumps-cases-hit-10-year-high/).

A map of the United States showing the locations of Minnesota, Washington, and Colorado can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4801141,106. - Mod.LK]
